---
import DocsNav from '../../components/DocsNav.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import SiteNav from '../../components/SiteNav.astro';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const systemDiagram = `flowchart LR
  User["User turns"]
  PR["PR / autopilot outcomes"]
  Config["learning config"]
  Sessions["chat_sessions + prompt snapshots"]
  Events["learning_events"]
  Reviews["learning_reviews"]
  Reviewer["Flue workflow + learning_reviewer"]
  Candidates["learning_candidates"]
  Memory["memories"]
  Audit["memory_events"]
  Skills["runtime skills"]
  Operator["Learning panel / CLI / API"]

  User --> Sessions
  Sessions --> Reviews
  PR --> Events
  Events --> Reviews
  Config --> Reviews
  Reviews --> Reviewer
  Reviewer --> Candidates
  Reviewer --> Memory
  Candidates --> Memory
  Candidates --> Skills
  Memory --> Audit
  Memory --> Sessions
  Skills --> Sessions
  Reviews --> Operator
  Candidates --> Operator
  Events --> Operator
  Audit --> Operator`;

const feedbackDiagram = `sequenceDiagram
  participant Work as Chat / PR work
  participant State as Neondeck SQLite
  participant Flue as Bounded Flue workflow
  participant Model as Self-improvement model
  participant Actions as Typed actions
  participant Session as Future session

  Work->>State: compact outcome or turn count
  State->>State: record learning_event or cadence counter
  State-->>Flue: threshold or manual trigger
  Flue->>State: prepare bounded evidence snapshot
  Flue->>Model: ask learning_reviewer for structured output
  Model-->>Flue: memoryActions and skillPatches
  Flue->>Actions: validate and apply or create candidates
  Actions->>State: write memories, candidates, audit events
  State->>Session: record stale signals as needed
  Session->>State: next prompt snapshot loads active memory
  Session-->>Work: improved behavior`;

const storeDiagram = `flowchart TB
  subgraph App["data/neondeck.db"]
    Memories["memories: current guidance"]
    MemoryEvents["memory_events: before / after audit"]
    LearningEvents["learning_events: triggers and outcomes"]
    LearningReviews["learning_reviews: bounded reviewer runs"]
    LearningCandidates["learning_candidates: review-mode decisions"]
    ChatSessions["chat_sessions: session metadata and loaded ids"]
    ConfigHistory["config_history: skill/config change audit"]
  end

  subgraph FlueDB["data/flue.db"]
    FlueRuns["Flue runs and agent runtime state"]
    Transcripts["display-assistant transcripts"]
  end

  subgraph Files["runtime-home files"]
    Skills["skills/ and built-in skill material"]
    Config["config.json"]
    Env[".env"]
  end

  Memories --> ChatSessions
  LearningReviews --> LearningCandidates
  LearningCandidates --> Memories
  LearningCandidates --> Skills
  Skills --> ConfigHistory
  FlueRuns --> LearningReviews
  Transcripts -. summaries only .-> ChatSessions`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Memory architecture · neondeck"
  description="A technical guide to Neondeck memory, learning reviews, audit state, and the feedback loop that improves future sessions."
>
  <div class="site-shell">
    <SiteNav />
    <main class="container docs-layout">
      <DocsNav />
      <article class="docs-prose memory-architecture">
        <h1>Memory architecture</h1>
        <p>
          Neondeck memory is deliberately small: it stores current guidance that
          should affect future sessions. It is not the transcript store, not the
          PR database, and not a generic knowledge graph. Those systems keep
          evidence. Memory keeps the distilled behavior Neon should carry
          forward.
        </p>

        <h2>Design review</h2>
        <p>
          The implementation follows three boundaries that are worth preserving.
          First, every write goes through typed Valibot-validated actions such
          as
          <code>neondeck_memory_learn</code>, <code
            >neondeck_memory_rewrite</code
          >,
          <code>neondeck_memory_merge</code>, <code
            >neondeck_memory_archive</code
          >, and the candidate decision actions. Second, model-backed learning
          runs as finite Flue workflows that prepare bounded evidence snapshots
          before calling the self-improvement model. Third, active sessions do
          not silently inherit new guidance. Config and skill changes are
          recorded as stale context, and memory events mark a session stale when
          they affect memory ids that were loaded into that session. New memory
          guidance loads on the next prompt snapshot or explicit refresh.
        </p>
        <p>
          That shape keeps the system close to the Hermes-style learning loop
          without turning memory into a vague dump of recent context. The model
          can suggest durable lessons, but SQLite state changes remain
          deterministic, auditable, and narrow.
        </p>

        <h2>System map</h2>
        <p>
          Memory sits between runtime evidence and future prompt snapshots.
          Conversation turns, PR outcomes, workflow summaries, and
          Kilo/autopilot facts are compacted into learning review inputs. The
          reviewer output can apply memory immediately, create review
          candidates, or propose skill patches.
        </p>
        <pre class="mermaid-block"><code>{systemDiagram}</code></pre>

        <h2>The feedback loop</h2>
        <p>
          The loop starts with work Neon already performs: chat turns, reviews,
          CI fixes, push-back attempts, recovery actions, and Kilo handoffs. The
          app records compact facts with stable ids so repeat observations do
          not inflate the learning signal. Cadence and threshold rules decide
          when a bounded Flue workflow should ask the self-improvement model for
          durable lessons.
        </p>
        <pre class="mermaid-block"><code>{feedbackDiagram}</code></pre>
        <p>
          The important constraint is that the model does not write arbitrary
          state. It returns structured <code>memoryActions</code> and
          <code>skillPatches</code>. Neondeck validates those outputs, rejects
          suspicious or secret-like content, and applies the result through the
          same action layer a human or dashboard uses.
        </p>

        <h2>Storage layout</h2>
        <p>
          Neondeck keeps app state separate from Flue runtime state. The app
          database stores memory, learning events, review records, candidates,
          session metadata, and audit history. Flue owns agent transcripts and
          workflow runtime state. Runtime-home files hold configuration,
          secrets, and user skills.
        </p>
        <pre class="mermaid-block"><code>{storeDiagram}</code></pre>

        <h2>Memory rows</h2>
        <p>
          Active writes use three scopes:
          <code>user</code> for durable user preferences,
          <code>local</code> for machine and tool facts, and
          <code>project</code> for repository or product conventions. Legacy
          <code>session</code> and <code>watch</code> rows are readable for compatibility,
          but new learning writes do not create them.
        </p>
        <p>
          A memory row is either <code>active</code> or <code>archived</code>.
          Active rows can load into prompt snapshots. Archived rows remain in
          history but stop shaping future sessions. Rewrites and merges keep
          guidance concise; archiving replaces deletion so the audit trail can
          explain what changed.
        </p>

        <h2>Review modes</h2>
        <p>
          Learning write policy is configurable. <code>off</code> records review results
          without changing memory. <code>review</code> creates candidates under <code
            >learning_candidates</code
          >. <code>auto</code> lets bounded workflows apply allowed memory changes
          through typed actions. Skill patch writes have their own mode and remain
          conservative: append-style automatic patches are possible, while whole-skill
          replacements require review.
        </p>

        <h2>Conversation reflection</h2>
        <p>
          Conversation reflection is cadence-based. After the configured turn
          interval, Neondeck queues <code>review_conversation_for_learning</code
          >. The workflow reviews compact session metadata, stored summaries,
          stale-context reasons, loaded memory ids, and current memory
          summaries. It does not copy raw Flue transcript pages into app state.
        </p>

        <h2>PR and autopilot retrospectives</h2>
        <p>
          PR learning is outcome-based. Neondeck records idempotent
          <code>pr_handled</code> events from Flue workflow observations and typed
          local API action results for autopilot, prepared-diff, recovery, and Kilo
          result paths. When the count reaches the configured retrospective threshold,
          <code>review_pr_batch_for_learning</code> reviews compact summaries and
          proposes durable memory or skill candidates.
        </p>

        <h2>Curation</h2>
        <p>
          Curation is the pruning mechanism. The
          <code>curate_learning_store</code> workflow reviews active memory, recent
          audit events, and configured limits. In review mode it proposes upserts,
          rewrites, merges, and archives as candidates. In auto mode, those same allowed
          actions can be applied directly after snapshot-target checks and typed action
          validation. The deterministic
          <code>neondeck_memory_curate</code> action is the narrower cleanup path
          for archive-oriented pruning.
        </p>

        <h2>Operator controls</h2>
        <p>
          Operators can inspect the entire loop through
          <code>GET /api/learning/state</code>, the Learning dashboard panel, or
          <code>neondeck learning ...</code>. That surface combines review
          records, memory candidates, skill patch candidates, memory audit
          events, and learning events. Candidate filters are sent to the backend
          before limits are applied so memory and skill queues stay visible
          independently.
        </p>

        <h2>Safety properties</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>All public memory and learning inputs are Valibot validated.</li>
          <li>
            Secret-like or prompt-injection-like memory values are rejected.
          </li>
          <li>
            Model output becomes proposals or typed action calls, not raw SQL.
          </li>
          <li>Memory changes are audited with before and after snapshots.</li>
          <li>
            Skill patches keep before/after hashes and can be restored only when
            the file still matches the audited patched content.
          </li>
          <li>
            Existing sessions stay stable until a new prompt snapshot is loaded.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Where to look in code</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <code>src/memory-actions.ts</code>: memory CRUD, candidates,
            curation, audit events, and write policy.
          </li>
          <li>
            <code>src/learning-reviews.ts</code>: conversation reflection,
            curation, PR retrospectives, and handled-event accounting.
          </li>
          <li>
            <code>src/learning-operator.ts</code>: consolidated read-only
            operator state.
          </li>
          <li>
            <code>src/skill-patches.ts</code>: skill patch proposal, apply,
            reject, audit, and restore.
          </li>
          <li>
            <code>src/workflows/review_conversation_for_learning.ts</code>, <code
              >src/workflows/curate_learning_store.ts</code
            >, and <code>src/workflows/review_pr_batch_for_learning.ts</code>:
            bounded Flue workflow entry points.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </article>
    </main>
    <SiteFooter />
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .memory-architecture {
    max-width: 900px;
  }

  .mermaid-block {
    border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cyan) 34%, var(--line));
    box-shadow: 0 0 0 1px rgba(105, 230, 255, 0.04);
  }

  .mermaid-block code {
    color: var(--code-ink);
  }
</style>
